</taxonomicName>
, rather than 
<taxonomicName id="88844D345345FF8BFBB58762FE1CFD31" authority="(Lyman 1879)" baseAuthorityName="Lyman" baseAuthorityYear="1879" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Ophiolebes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiacanthida" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="antarctica">
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA55345FF8BFBB58762FEA1FD30" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">O. antarctica</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="2B154B465345FF8BFF2E8786FE03FD31" author="Lyman, T." box="[282,427,645,671]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" pagination="17 - 83" refId="ref33210" refString="Lyman, T. (1879) Ophiuridae and Astrophytidae of the exploring voyage of H. M. S. Challenger under Prof. Sir Wyville Thomson, F. R. S. Part 2. Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology, Harvard University, 6, 17 - 83, pls. 11 - 19." type="journal article" year="1879">Lyman 1879</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
that has been recorded from Antarctic and subantarctic regions, on both morphological and bathymetric evidence. The specimens have a mix of granules and short conical stumps on the disc (
<figureCitation id="D7BF2A325345FF8BFB0087ABFA27FD6D" box="[1332,1423,680,707]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1918,1942]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1894]" captionTargetId="figure-26@18.[151,1436,181,1894]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 6. (A) Ophiacantha veterna, MNHN IE.2009.1562, dorsal outline. (B) MNHN IE.2009.1563, ventral view. (C–E) Ophiosabine cuspidata, MNHN IE.2009.1558, C: dorsal outline, D: dorsal view, E: ventral view. (F) Ophiotreta spectabilis, MNHN IE.2009.1564, dorsal view. (G–H) Ophiolimna bairdi, MNHN IE.2009.1571, G: dorsal and H: ventral views." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404692" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404692/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Fig. 6G</figureCitation>
), characteristic of 
<taxonomicName id="88844D345345FF8BFF6187CEFE14FD48" baseAuthorityName="Lyman" baseAuthorityYear="1883" box="[341,444,716,743]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Ophiolimna" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiacanthida" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="bairdi">
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA55345FF8BFF6187CEFE14FD48" box="[341,444,716,743]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">O. bairdi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, rather than the uniform granule-shaped armament of 
<taxonomicName id="88844D345345FF8BFA1C87CEFB15FD48" baseAuthorityName="Lyman" baseAuthorityYear="1879" box="[1064,1213,717,743]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Ophiolebes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiacanthida" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="antarctica">
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA55345FF8BFA1C87CEFB15FD48" box="[1064,1213,717,743]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">O. antarctica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Moreover, records from the north Atlantic have been generally found at 
<quantity id="887C9B525345FF8BFCD387F3FC2CFCA5" box="[743,900,752,779]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.75" metricValueMax="2.5" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" unit="m" value="1750.0" valueMax="2500.0" valueMin="1000.0">1000–2500 m</quantity>
, whereas those in the southern polar regions are generally above 
<quantity id="887C9B525345FF8BFF678616FE04FC81" box="[339,428,789,815]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" unit="m" value="1000.0">1000 m</quantity>
. Phylogenetic evidence in 
<bibRefCitation id="2B154B465345FF8BFCE98617FBBAFC81" author="Christodoulou, M. &amp; O'Hara, T. D. &amp; Hugall, A. F. &amp; Arbizu, P. M." box="[733,1042,788,815]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" pagination="3909 - 3912" refId="ref29723" refString="Christodoulou, M., O'Hara, T. D., Hugall, A. F. &amp; Arbizu, P. M. (2019) Dark Ophiuroid Biodiversity in a Prospective Abyssal Mine Field. Current Biology, 29 (e 3), 3909 - 3912." type="journal article" year="2019">
Christodoulou 
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA55345FF8BFDB28616FC17FC80" box="[902,959,788,814]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">et al.</emphasis>
(2019)
</bibRefCitation>
suggests that tropical Indo-Pacific specimens identified by 
<bibRefCitation id="2B154B465345FF8BFF80863AFD70FCFD" author="O'Hara, T. D. &amp; Stohr, S." box="[436,728,824,851]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" pagination="33 - 141" refId="ref35165" refString="O'Hara, T. D. &amp; Stohr, S. (2006) Deep water Ophiuroidea (Echinodermata) of New Caledonia: Ophiacanthidae and Hemieuryalidae. Tropical Deep-Sea Benthos, 24, 33 - 141." type="journal article" year="2006">O’Hara and Stöhr (2006)</bibRefCitation>
as 
<taxonomicName id="88844D345345FF8BFD31863AFC35FCFC" baseAuthorityName="Lyman" baseAuthorityYear="1879" box="[773,925,825,851]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Ophiolebes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiacanthida" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="antarctica">
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA55345FF8BFD31863AFC35FCFC" box="[773,925,825,851]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">O. antarctica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are a separate species related to 
<taxonomicName id="88844D345345FF8BFB11863AFEE2FCD9" authority="(Koehler 1904)" baseAuthorityName="Koehler" baseAuthorityYear="1904" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Ophiolimna" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiacanthida" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="perfida">
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA55345FF8BFB11863AFA34FCFC" box="[1317,1436,824,851]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">O. perfida</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="2B154B465345FF8BFEAB865FFEE9FCD9" author="Koehler, R." box="[159,321,860,887]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" pagination="1 - 176" refId="ref32152" refString="Koehler, R. (1904) Ophiures de mer profonde. Siboga-Expeditie, 45, 1 - 176 pls. 1 - 36." type="journal article" year="1904">Koehler 1904</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. Specimens from the Galapagos Islands, although appearing broadly similar in appearance, are placed in a separate genetic lineage (
<bibRefCitation id="2B154B465345FF8BFC058683FCFCFC35" author="Christodoulou, M. &amp; O'Hara, T. D. &amp; Hugall, A. F. &amp; Arbizu, P. M." box="[561,852,896,923]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" pagination="3909 - 3912" refId="ref29723" refString="Christodoulou, M., O'Hara, T. D., Hugall, A. F. &amp; Arbizu, P. M. (2019) Dark Ophiuroid Biodiversity in a Prospective Abyssal Mine Field. Current Biology, 29 (e 3), 3909 - 3912." type="journal article" year="2019">
Christodoulou 
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA55345FF8BFCEE8682FCBBFC34" box="[730,787,896,922]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">et al.</emphasis>
2019
</bibRefCitation>
, DNA code=NA064-015-13-A_EP_3).
</paragraph>
